Problem 1. (7 pts)

  1. Consider the bill_depth_mm variable in the penguins data frame (see lectures 3 and 4). Review the documentation for the penguins dataset to answer, what does this variable describe? (1pt)

Answer - The variable bill_depth_mm describes a number denoting bill depth (millimeters).

  1. Are bill_depth_mm vs.bill_length_mm related? Use ggplot, as in lectures 3 and 4, to produce a scatterplot with bill_depth_mm on the y-axis and bill_length_mm on the x-axis, to help you answer this question. Describe the overall relationship between these two variables. Include an appropriate geom_smooth object mapped at the appropriate level (global level or geom); see lecture. (2pt)

Answer - The trend line in the scatterplot of bill_depth_mm vs.bill_length_mm slopes from top to bottom which is a negative slope, this indicates that there is a negative correlation between the two variables. It means that, as the bill length increases, the bill depth tends to decrease, on average. This suggests that penguins with longer bills tend to have shallower (less deep) bills, and penguins with shorter bills tend to have deeper (thicker) bills.

ggplot(
  data = penguins,
  mapping = aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = bill_depth_mm))+
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")+
    labs(
    title = "Bill length and Bill depth relation")

  1. Now take into account the species as well. Use ggplot, to produce a scatterplot with bill_depth_mm on the y-axis and bill_length_mm on the x-axis, and species as the color and shape, to help you answer this question. Describe the overall relationship between these two variables based on this plot and this dataset. Include an appropriate geom_smooth object mapped at the appropriate level (global level or geom); see lecture. (2pt)

Answer - The relationship between bill length and bill depth differs by species. Some species, like Adelie and Chinstrap, show a negative relationship, while others, like Gentoo, may show a different trend. Adelie and Chinstrap likely have a negative correlation between bill length and bill depth, with longer bills associated with shallower depths. Gentoo may show a different pattern, possibly no clear trend or a slight positive correlation.

ggplot(
  data = penguins,
  mapping = aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = bill_depth_mm, color = species, shape = species))+
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(
    title = "Bill length and Bill depth as per species")

  1. Use ggplot to visualize the distribution of the carat variable in the diamonds dataset through a histogram. Experiment with different binwidths (use at least 4). (2pts)

Answer -

ggplot(
  data = diamonds, 
  mapping = aes(x = carat)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1, fill = "steelblue", color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Diamond Carat Values (Binwidth = 0.1)"
  )

ggplot(
  data = diamonds, 
  mapping = aes(x = carat)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.2, fill = "darkorange", color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Diamond Carat Values (Binwidth = 0.2)"
  )

ggplot(
  data = diamonds, 
  mapping = aes(x = carat)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.03, fill = "lightgreen", color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Diamond Carat Values (Binwidth = 0.03)"
  )

ggplot(
  data = diamonds, 
  mapping = aes(x = carat)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.05, fill = "purple", color = "black") +

    title = "Diamond Carat Values (Binwidth = 0.05)"
  )

  1. What binwidth reveals the most interesting patterns? Discuss briefly. (1pt)

Answer - Binwidth = 0.05 reveals the most interesting patterns. It provides a good balance between granularity and smoothness, allowing to observe key features of the data, such as peaks, gaps, and overall distribution shape.

  1. Generate a boxplot for carats using ggplot. Use the documentation and explain what each part of the boxplot represents. (2pts)

Answer - The box represents the middle 50% of the data, with the length of the box indicating the interquartile range (IQR), which spans from the 25th percentile to the 75th percentile of the dataset. A line in the center of the box marks the median, or the 50th percentile, which shows the central tendency. The position of these lines helps illustrate the overall spread of the data and whether its symmetrically distributed or skewed.

Individual points outside the box represent outliersthese are observations that fall beyond 1.5 times the IQR from either side of the box, meaning they are unusually high or low values.

The whiskers extending from the box show the range of the data, stretching to the most extreme points that are still within the non-outlier range. These whiskers stop at the farthest data points that are not considered outliers.

ggplot(
  data = diamonds, 
  mapping = aes(y = carat)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "lightblue", color = "black")+
  labs(
    title = "Carat Values in Diamonds")
